<subSubSection id="02C66578FFE7FFA2FC959BA16BCB7CF6" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="28" pageId="10" pageNumber="24" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="4A6336F3FFE7FFA2FC959BA16BCB7CF6" blockId="10.[831,1437,2021,2078]" lastBlockId="14.[151,756,257,407]" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="28" pageId="10" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis id="78A8EAE1FFE7FFA6FC959BA16ABD7A9C" bold="true" box="[831,944,2021,2045]" pageId="10" pageNumber="24">Remarks:</emphasis>
It is characterized by a planispiral and closely coiled test. The wall of the test is very finely arenaceous. 
<emphasis id="78A8EAE1FFE3FFA2FF3D9D4568C47C78" bold="true" box="[151,457,257,281]" pageId="14" pageNumber="28">Stratigraphic distribution:</emphasis>
This species is recorded in Europe from the Early Cretaceous to the Late Cretaceous (CUSHMAN, 1946). It apparently has a wide range in the American Late Cretaceous. It is found in the Maastrichtian (Abu Zeneima Member) of the Esh El Mallaha area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
